aa(lp185
VMost people don't know about Samuel Pierpont Langley.
p186
aVAnd back in the early 20th century,
p187
aVthe pursuit of powered man flight was like the dot com of the day.
p188
aVEverybody was trying it.
p189
aVAnd Samuel Pierpont Langley had, what we assume,
p190
aVto be the recipe for success.
p191
aVEven now, you ask people,
p192
aV"Why did your product or why did your company fail?"
p193
aVand people always give you the same permutation
p194
aVof the same three things:
p195
aVunder-capitalized, the wrong people, bad market conditions.
p196
aVIt's always the same three things, so let's explore that.
p197
aVSamuel Pierpont Langley
p198
aVwas given 50,000 dollars by the War Department
p199
aVto figure out this flying machine.
p200
aVMoney was no problem.
p201
aVHe held a seat at Harvard
p202
aVand worked at the Smithsonian and was extremely well-connected;
p203
aVhe knew all the big minds of the day.
p204
aVHe hired the best minds money could find
p205
aVand the market conditions were fantastic.
p206
aVThe New York Times followed him around everywhere,
p207
aVand everyone was rooting for Langley.
p208
aVThen how come we've never heard of Samuel Pierpont Langley?
p209
aa(lp210
VA few hundred miles away in Dayton, Ohio,
p211
aVOrville and Wilbur Wright,
p212
aVthey had none of what we consider to be the recipe for success.
p213
aVThey had no money;
p214
aVthey paid for their dream with the proceeds from their bicycle shop.
p215
aVNot a single person on the Wright brothers' team
p216
aVhad a college education,
